    <passage>
      <offset>46</offset>
      <infon key="type">body</infon>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">2</infon>
        <offset>46</offset>
        <text>Advances in iron biogeochemistry have transformed our understanding of the oceanic iron cycle over the past three decades: multiple sources of iron to the ocean were discovered, including dust, coastal and shallow sediments, sea ice and hydrothermal fluids.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">3</infon>
        <offset>304</offset>
        <text>This new iron is rapidly recycled in the upper ocean by a range of organisms; up to 50% of the total soluble iron pool is turned over weekly in this way in some ocean regions.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">4</infon>
        <offset>480</offset>
        <text>For example, bacteria dissolve particulate iron and at the same time release compounds -- iron-binding ligands -- that complex with iron and therefore help to keep it in solution.
</text>
